segments.text: He says, just because you're the lowest ranking table doesn't mean that you don't have an opinion.
I said, don't you?
I have.
He says, well, tell us.
I said, Mr. Secretary, when y'all get through with that top man, don't send him back to us in Texas.
Well, that broke up the meeting because McNamara

strong but he wasn't as strong as people thought he was if he didn't have both the hand of kennedy and johnson behind him no secretary of defense is as strong as mcnamara appeared to be on the surface unless full faith and confidence of the boss
McNamara's a smart individual.
Very smart.
Very intelligent.
Not a practical guy.
Some of the people that he picked up to support him were not particularly, I don't think, as bright as they gave him credit for.
For example?
Well, one of the
people that helped dictate what was going on in Vietnam, had a status room.
And there in Washington, D.C., in the Pentagon, some of these people would actually go through exercises of sin.
Well, now, what if we moved a squad of eight men from here over to here?
Now, you know, that's like me giving permission for a couple of GS-14s to sit and play tic-tac-toos all day.
because nobody in Washington is going to move eight men in Vietnam from here to there.
But, you know, this is not an exception.
I mean, this is a rule that they play such silly games, you know.
So, in other words, they try to control the situation.
Oh, yeah.
What was the general attitude towards Secretary McNamara and the Pentagon?
mixed emotions, naturally there would be.
You're definitely going to get them in the military because I personally think, and there's no way of knowing, I personally think the military is a little more inclined to be a conservative GOP.
The officers.
I don't know about you.
And whenever you get a bunch of them and they're having to work for a democratic administration, well, a democratic administration, you get uneasy feelings and so on.
Sure, they'll carry out to the best of their ability and whatever the boss says, that goes.
But for instance, both McCone and Turner,
knew full well that I was a conservative Republican.
They were Democrats.
And I stayed in that office eight years.
No, five years.
One year under the first one and four years under the second one.
So you never had any problem as far as political philosophies?
The idea is to get the job done.
That's right.
That would have nothing to do with anybody.
under a democratic administration.
There was never any pressure on you while you were in the military to vote a certain way?
No, not at all.
Okay.
So much for McNamara.
Now, you said, didn't you say yesterday when we were talking that at this time you met Harold Brown, who became Secretary of Defense under Jimmy Carter?
Did you say that?
No, see, Harold Brown was the next Secretary of the Air Force following Gene Zucker.
And that's where I met and knew Harold Brown pretty much on an intimate situation at that time.
Because it was while I was in the Secretary's office that the Air Force felt that it needed another base in Vietnam.
And you have to go back and
Well, who's in control and why and where?
McVie, the top guy in Vietnam, of course, was an army troop.
The theater that this war was being fought in belonged to the Navy.
whose top headquarters was in Hawaii.
The Air Force doesn't need another base.
Well, first the Air Force had to prove that it needed another base to put more fighters in the Vietnam.
After that was proved, then
The Air Force had to either get the pressure put on to the Navy, who was responsible for all construction in Vietnam.
The Army wasn't responsible for construction, but the Navy was.
Okay.
Make the resources available to build the base.
Here's the money.
We don't have the resources.
Still, the...
don't need the base because now the resources are such that we don't have the resources.
Of course, the Navy didn't want the base because its forte was to put the carriers offshore and fly the missions from the carriers.
If the Air Force couldn't get a place to put their fighters, there was no way they could fly them.
Clark was too far, too long a leg to fly a mission in on the fighter and bring it back down.
Okay, so the Air Force went back now and said, prove to them that they needed a base in Vietnam.
In other words, took it out of the JCCS and the services and went to the, at the secretary level,

we've proven that we need the fighters we got to have this base but we want permission from you for the air force to contract for and to execute and build the base and the air force will supervise the construction not touch any of the resources that are already in country we'll go in there and design the base bring the contractor in won't bother anybody else logistically
and build a base and then pull it back out.
The project was named Turnkey.
And that was exactly what it was, Turnkey.
No logistics support required from anything that was already in country.
Well, McNamara thought he'd work it back and forth, tore it apart, put it back together.
finally one day made the decision to do it.
Go ahead.
Well, this tore the Navy apart because it invaded their area in which they were responsible for construction.
And it tore the Army apart because the Army
had for years been trying to limit how much capability the Air Force actually developed to do design and construction.
See, under the Key West Agreement, way back when Truman was president, they divided the world.
And we got England, the United Kingdom, the Air Force.
The rest of the world was divided between the Army and the Navy.
Well, the first exception was we got to do our own Air Force Academy.
Then the next exception was we got to do our own housing worldwide.

And all this time, others were beginning to see us growing a capability that would compete with them and push down their organization because their organization was large enough to do not only their own but ours too, namely the Corps of Engineers.
Right.
Right.
Okay.
Anyway, we got permission from McNamara to do turnkey.
Where is the base supposed to be built?
Beg your pardon?
Where was the base supposed to be located?
Okay.
We took representatives from four contracting firms to that net.
Colonel by the name of McGarvey from the air staff, myself, were the escort officers to take them over
Here are the sites.
We showed them two sites.
One was in Wei.
We were there the day that the North Vietnamese overran the border and started pushing people out of Wei.
But anyway, that was one of the sites that had been approved.
What year was this?
And the other was Tui Wah.
Well, that would be...
This wasn't during Tet Offensive, was it?
Yes.
It was the start of the Tet.
So it was January 31st, 1968.
Okay.
Good on the date.
That's your job, isn't it?
Yeah.
That was 10.
But it seems to me that it should be sooner than that.
It was earlier than that.
Because the buildup was 65.
I know, but see, I left.
I left.
So it couldn't have been Tet.
It would have had to be when the initial build-up, which was 1965 in Vietnam.
That would be more logical.
Well, it was in the Johnson administration, sure.
So it would be in...

667 uh 66. still the secretary of defense he resigned in 67 so late 66. okay okay anyway we took these contractors over and showed them the two sites the other site was tuyawa t-u-y-h-o-a and tuyawa was the one that was ultimately chosen and mcgarvey was
the air staff project officer, and I was the secretary project officer.
McGarvey was a full colonel, and I was lieutenant colonel.
Following the completion, he made BG, and I made full colonel.
And it was a practice that

We had a weekly report on Secretary Brown's desk Friday night before leaving the Pentagon that gave him a complete rundown of everything that had taken place at that week, gave him the status of all the construction, the yards poured, what percent of completion of the runway was, a whole nine yards.
This was quite an exercise because
Everything was across the beach.
There was no dock.
It was offloading the ships on the lighters and bring the lighters across the beach.
And this was everything.
All of the construction material, all the fuel, all the food, the whole work, everything came across the beach.
Because again, nothing was levied on or taxed anything that was already there.
And to make matters worse,
We were told that we would stay within the dollar appropriation that had been granted to build the base.
There was no additional money, and we would not go back to Congress and ask for additional money.
So this gave both McGarvey and me no end of problems, because whenever there was a cost overrun on one element, across all these miles, we had to work out with those people over there, OK,
What are we going to give up, or what are we going to change the quality of to cover that essential?
And back and forth, back and forth, both.
One of the American firms then took the job?
Yes.
Abasco of New York, which is an electric bond and share company, was the prime holding company that took the job.
Their forte is really power plants.
I mean, big, huge power plants.
They are one of the largest outfits in the United States.
Why do they want an airfield?
I don't know.
What kind of job do they do?
They're an outstanding job.
But they're a big subcontractor for paving and the runways and the roads.
underground and utilities and so on, with a firm out of Florida that had worked on the Kennedy Raceways and things like that down there.
And it was a real good organization that they put together.
Did they hire Vietnamese to do the manual labor?
Oh, yes.
Sure, sure.
And Stan McGarvey was promoted to Colonel.
It would be on the site.
supervisor, the Air Force colonel, he too was promoted to general.
So people were properly rewarded.

Again, we held it within the funds that were available and reported back to Congress, reported to the Department of Defense, and when the contractor was through, when everybody retreated right back over the beaches and came on home, and the birds flew in, took over the base, and so on.
How long did it take to build?
About 14 months, 16 months.
Was it effective as far as the area?
Oh yes, very definitely.
Because they were flying missions off of it before it was completed.
It was in a very, very peculiar location security-wise because just 60 miles south of there, there never was complete
clean out of the communists.
I mean, they were that close all the time.
Whereabouts was it?
Well, it would be north of Cumberland Bay.
OK.
I know where that is.
Off Highway 1, huh?
Yeah.
So it's in between Hawaii and Cam Ranh Bay.
Yeah.
I had an interesting trip to Cam Ranh Bay too.
Tell me about that.
We went into Cam Ranh Bay when before anything had ever taken place other than the fact that some engineer troops were in there
cutting roads for the Army Depot portion of Comron.

And I was accompanying my boss, Mr. Turner at the time, and the top civilian engineer from the Department of Defense was a man by the name of Ed Sheridan, and he was along in the group and took us in a big fly and had a
makeshift map on the wall.
Here are the roads we're cutting, and here are the ones we've already cut.
And we had flown out of the Tron in, what was the transport called?
I don't know.
The Army transport or something.
And they had met at, huh?
I don't know.
What a little thing.
Oh.
From the trough down the combine.
Because they had no landing.
We just landed on dirt.
And they had met us out there with jeeps and machine guns mounted all over the thing.
And, you know, they took us in.
They started briefing.
And here's what we're doing.
And we're definitely here.
And finally he says, are there any questions?
Mr. Sheridan from the Department of Defense says, what's that line?
He says, well, this is Army and that's Air Force, and we're told that they're going to build a base over here, but we don't know anything about it, and we kind of doubt that they'll ever materialize.
Well, actually, as we had flown over, we saw our contractors.

They were already clearing the field and clearing the way for the first runway to go in to Comron Bay, and here this colonel was briefing about what was going on on this side of the line, and there was construction going over on the other side of the line.
He says...
But we don't think it'll ever come about.
Well, the contractor from the Navy, I mean, all that was contracted through the Navy, was in there clearing it.
So we took off, and we certainly didn't give it a big wave when I was back.
But this was the clearing to put the AM2 mat down, which was the runway, I'm going to say.
All in all, I had seven trips to Vietnam and six to Thailand during that time.
Why in Thailand?
Well, we had a number of bases in Thailand.
Yeah.
And you were building on them?
Well, we were building on them.
And then we were building a project that had a number of names and nicknames.
The windmill was one.
But it was right up on the Laos.
Thai border, and it was the big intelligence consolidation area that they were picking up things out of Vietnam and so on at that location, and then relaying them on back.
But it was one of the largest projects over there, run by the security service.
I guess it was under construction for a while.
A year and a half, I guess.

But a lot of the stuff that they dropped along the Ho Chi Minh Trail were, not being one, so I don't know, but some type of pickup communication devices and things like that that they could sense, oh, but sense how much tonnage was coming down the trail just by air.
But that was tucked away up in the jungle.
But we had three active bases that fighters were all over.
Thailand also is a wonderful place to visit compared to Vietnam.
You felt a little bit more comfortable in Bangkok than you did in Vietnam.
What were the conditions like in Vietnam?
Uh, in Vietnam I'd say they were, uh, they varied so much, you know.
You could, uh, get one place and have fairly decent quarters and vests, and another place, uh, often wondered whether you were ever going to find the luxury of these hanoms, uh, the, uh,
here in the city, always wondering about security.
I personally stayed out of the more popular places, because that's where all the trouble was.
There were other places most of the time for us to go,
Traveling at the level we were at, we needed to stay in certain quarters that weren't used and were pretty well guarded.
We so desired to have a meal right there at the quarters.
The hours were such that work late and get up early and start again.
We're not there to
to spend a lifetime with her and get that done and get out of there.
So you don't fall into the custom way of a person who is assigned over there lives or plays or, quote, enjoys life.
What about inter-service rivalry?
We've alluded to some of that.
It's been eight years in Washington, DC.
Did you see a lot of inter-service rivalry?
I've got to address that in two parts.
The time that I was in the Secretary of the Air Force office and back and forth and working with the Navy and some agencies of the Army for the things that had to go on in Vietnam.
Yeah.
And yet, at that time, we had a
a director of civil engineering down in the military, named Bob Curtin, who was a pretty smart individual.
And he tried to eliminate some of this rivalry by establishing what he called exchange officers with the other services.
Let's get some of our people working for you and some of yours working for us, and we can get rid of this bickering and so on.
That's all well and good.
But the bickering doesn't really go on on the work level.
Captains and majors and lieutenant colonels can work like heck with each other.
This is the job.
Get it done.
Goddamn colonels and generals would like to do the bickering.
Hey, that's our job.
Y'all back out of that.
What can you get put?
Oh, four or five weeks.
Well, hell, we've got to have it done tomorrow.
It can't happen.
It's our job.
We'll get it done.
Their priorities don't fit their priorities.
There's always a reason why.
But then I jumped all the way over when I went to the Department of Defense as a general officer and was a director in the Department of Defense, dealing with all four services.
And believe it or not, I had more problems with my own service than I did with the Army and the Navy and the Marines.
What do you mean?

coming out of the Department of Defense and saying, okay, here's a project we want to work out, or here's a policy we want to get established, and I'd have no problem with the Army or the Navy or the Marines, but I'd find guys in the Air Force fighting the hell out of me.
You know?
How can you count for that?
You know, the Air Force likes to step back and look and think and...
Some of the others go, okay, if the higher echelon wants it done this way, this is the way we'll do it.
A little bit different look at discipline, I guess you could call it.
So you think that the Air Force is not as disciplined now or more thoughtful?
More thoughtful.
I gave a hell of a lot of thought in operation and maintenance of facilities.
Now, see, that was the forte that I was in, not combat or not
personnel policy, but in the operation and maintenance of facilities.
At that time, I was director of facility maintenance, and this is what we would be talking about.
Facilities being housing, the whole work.
But the Air Force had set itself up and had established the credentials of, boy, we are the experts in operation and maintenance.
Even though the Army's been doing it and the Navy's been doing it years longer than we have, we're the experts.
And had spent a lot of money to get their people pretty well trained.
Because having responsibility for design and construction in so small part of the world, their major effort was put in
to operation and maintenance of the soldiers.

And therefore, they quickly claimed to be the experts, whereas the other engineering services for Army, Navy, and Marines, the Army and the Navy, they had to spread themselves over design, construction, operation, and maintenance, and try to be experts in all of it.
The Air Force did have
I think probably a little bit higher degree of expertise.
But again, just the cooperation is what I was thinking at this level.
I had more, I had bigger problems with my own service than I did with the others.
And this was later on, but you had asked about the service rivalry, and that was back in the early days.
There are a couple of things that were, let's see, on the good news side, I call that bad news side, that I was involved in while in the Air Force Secretary's office.
The Air Force Museum
is located at Wright-Patterson Airport Station, Ohio.
You can go to many air bases and you'll see gathering of old airplanes.
The real museum is at Wright-Patterson.
It is not a public finance facility or installation.
It was privately endowed.
It was built by
subscriptions, by donations, by every way imaginable.
Tax money was not used to build it.
But at the same time, since it was built on an Air Force installation, the Secretary chose to have a real tight control over what type of facility was built and so on.
Well, the minute the Secretary did that, then
Mr. Turner, it's your job.
You carry it out.
Mr. Turner, come in here.
Let's talk about the museum.
So I ended up being initially the recorder on the Air Force Museum board.
And we went through a couple of years of fighting out what type of facility would be built.
of the Air Force Logistics Command, a man by the name of Merrill.
And Merrill listened to everything that went back and forth.
And he and Luke Turner were real good friends.
Both of them had come up in the controller business.
And they were real good friends.
And it had been proposed
initially by the board to go along with the design of an architect engineer firm in Hartford, Connecticut.
And this design, we felt, that is the board, as well as the recorder, was going to end up being a monument to the capability of the architect engineer
rather than a museum for the Air Force.
It was going to be something that people would just look at and forget what was on the inside.
And something that we could never reach in dollar payments.
The amount of money that we had subscribed and collected was up in the $4 million, $5 million, and $6 million.
But this thing was up in the $18 million, $20 million, and $25 million.
We were talking about some dollars back there.
So General Merrill, who's a four-star, asked Turner to have me meet him in Hartford.
We spent the whole day up there listening to the architects and engineers.
Then we went out to the airport, left them alone and went out to the airport.
And he had his plane away from taking back to Ohio, and I had a commercial to go back to Washington.
And we sat down for an hour.
And he says, what do you recommend?
I said, General, I hate to tell you this, because this is probably not what you want to hear.
But I said, I think we ought to scrub it and start over.
He said, those are my sentiments also.
He said, as long as you and I never change,
He took off, popped, and we started all over again.
We scrubbed that architect.
We started again.
We've got something back that was within reach.
We've got a beautiful museum up there now.
Thousands of people daily come into that thing.
I think we've got one I've ever heard the airport has ever flown that's on static display and all types of everything.
It's a beautiful museum.
Why in Ohio instead of out at the Academy?
Well, because Wright-Patterson is the headquarters of the Air Force Logistics Command and two of the divisions of the Aeronautics of Air Force Systems Command.
Systems Command does the research and development.
Log Command does
the supply and the modifications once they're into the inventory.
So that is really the center of where all of the research development is done and where all of the maintenance and modifications are directed from.
The two divisions of the Air Force Systems Command are the technology, which is foreign technology, and one of the research divisions.
So it is a better place, really, than the Air Force Museum.
Really, I guess, pulls more people than something way out in Colorado.
You can keep getting repeats out there, but in Ohio, you get different people all the time.
I don't know why they come through there in the wintertime.
I hate it in the wintertime.
But anyway, that board then grew to the Air Force Academy Expansion Board.
The job was over for the museum.
From then on, it was execution.
That was up to the people at Wright and Pack.
Oh, we kept an eye on it.
Then we went from there to the Air Force Academy expansion.
That's when Congress permitted the Air Force Academy to go from 2,500 students to 4,417.
When it was first formed, it was smaller than
And then they enlarged it, the authorization.
And with that, we had to build more dorm space, more classroom space, add on to the dining hall.
We had all of this to do.
And this all came right on the tail of building one of the largest field houses that you and I will ever have seen.
It is a fabulous field house.
We had the field house under control.
Again, Turner put it under control.
You do not have a nickel over the appropriation.
I will not go back to Congress and ask for one nickel more than has been appropriated.
He told this to General Curtin, and he said, my dog catcher is hugged.
He's going to watch every dollar.
got to establish a direct communication between HUB and the man in Colorado, and it's not going to get one nickel more.
He didn't get one nickel more.
Again, it would swap out and everything else.
But beautiful.
Then we went on in to overseeing the expansion of the academy.
But like I said earlier, the Air Force did have special permission to do its own design and construction work for its academy without having to go to the Corps of Engineers or so on.
The, this board had, I've used the name Sheridan, the man from the Department of Defense was on it.
The superintendent of the Air Force Academy, of course, was on the board.
Those are the two that really played a role in what I was doing and then later on.
What was the end result?
The end result was on time as the wing built up and grunted people in.
Oh, certainly we had problems.
Glass in that part of the country is a hard thing to control.
Different coefficient of expansions of glass and metal trim caused all types of popping of glass, sand blowing.
And that part of the country etched glass that we didn't foresee.
So we had to go back and raise the standards and the hardness of glass and so on.
But it's a beautiful facility.
A&M will even envy some of the things that they've done.
They have, for instance,
A&M doesn't really need it because it gets cold at College Station.
I know that.
But it doesn't get cold like it does out there.
But when the cadets march into the dining hall at the Air Force Academy, they go through a screen that they never see.
And it's a double screen of warm air blowing both from the floor and the ceiling to keep the cold air from coming in with the cadets.
so that the inside of the dining hall never feels the draft when those doors open and cadets marching in.
And they just march through these two screens, and the temperature inside never changes.
Can you imagine that on the dining hall of the college station?
Oh, man.
Fabulous.
Fantastic.
So those are the two good things that you feel that happened from 1963 to 1968 when you were working in the Secretary's office.
On the outside, again, I was doing Boy Scout work.
I don't know how much you know about the Boy Scouts, but I was given a silver beaver at that time by the Boy Scouts.
So I did have time to do some other things.
Good.

tremendous i was uh wondering then how exactly how your functions and duties changed when you went from master planning to the secretary of the army's office secretary airport yeah i'm sorry of course well of course i took the master planning response i mean the access road responsibility with me so uh in master planning that was that was
worrying about, oh, a fourth of my time.
And as I got to the secretary's office, I guess it dropped to about, oh, maybe a fifth or sixth of my time.
And then these other things picked up.
The museum, the academy, the base in Vietnam, and different problems.
I initially went to the secretary's office to be just a straight exec to the civilians.
And that's what I was the first year under Alan McComb.
But when Turner came in, he said, man, you ain't about to be an executive.
He said, I'm giving you a job, a specific thing that you're responsible for.
And what did you think of that?
I thought that was great.
I said, what are we going to do about the executive?
He said, I've already got another military authorization.
And you tell me which one of those colonels down there you want.
And we just brought in another lieutenant colonel, and he became the exec.
He kept tabs on everything that was going on.
Well, why did they switch you to specific jobs instead of keep you as the exec?
Because he wanted me doing functional work, doing things that he was responsible for.
Whereas the exec, it's an important role, but then he keeps his finger on everything that's going on in the office.
He's really kind of responsible for nothing except what the boss specifically says.
You do this and come back to me.
Oh, I'd rather have the functional role.
Because in the other four years, I did engineering and construction.
And I did operation and maintenance.
And got into the problem and had things at that level.
Now, I wanted to ask you about Vietnam since.
You had been there a number of times, although you weren't in the combat in Vietnam itself.
I'm sure that you must have some ideas on this.
Why did we lose the war in Vietnam?
I wouldn't even tell you.
Okay.
Tell me about Harold Brown.
You started talking about him, but you said you got to know him very well, but you never described him.
What type of person is he?
Well, Heron Brown, when he was Secretary of the Air Force, was probably the most contemporary thinker with real strong technological ability
that that level is probably never seen.
You've got to remember that that's one level below the Secretary of Defense.
And there's nothing else like it in our government.
Because as the Secretary of the Air Force, even though he was under a cabinet man, he probably had more power than some of the people that were on the cabinet.
well-educated individual that was always ahead in thinking.
You could talk to a man or brief him, and you knew damn good and well that he was five or ten minutes ahead of you, but at the same time, the guy that had the patience to hear you through.
I never saw the man get impatient
Man with a good sense of humor.
Now, I'm saying this when he was Secretary of the Air Force.
I'd still not know him as anytime in his role in the Department of Defense.
But you thought he was a good leader at the Air Force?
Oh, yes.
Very good.
Gene Zuckert is what the Air Force needed.
Gene was a lawyer.
Harold Brown
a technical man.
But Gene was what we needed when the Air Force was down and building up fast.
Brown was what we needed when, OK, let's start thinking about the future and research and development.
Let's start putting some chips in the long range and see if there are not systems that are lying out there waiting to be discovered and so on.
And this is what we were talking about the other day.
We need both the practitioner and we need that thinker in that reserve.
Okay, let's move to the United Kingdom.
Your next job with the Third Air Force as the Deputy Chief of Staff from 1968 to 1970.
Okay, let me tell you a little bit about how I got there.
Go ahead.
During the last year that I worked in Secretary's office, I had made up my mind to retire.
And I had put in my retirement papers and
was even taking a physical, a retirement physical, at the airport hospital at Andrews.
Why'd you decide to retire?
Well, I was a reserve officer at that time.
And it's a strange thing in personnel work, but I was on active duty as a lieutenant colonel, but I was a permanent colonel in the reserve.
And I couldn't see getting
anywhere getting promoted and I had 27 years in which gave me close to the maximum for retirement and I would have retired as a pro-Colonel Payne rather than a Lieutenant Colonel even though
My active duty grade was only lieutenant colonel.
As a reserve officer, I was a full colonel, and that's what I was retired of.
